  "prompt": "What are some good sources for free instrumental music to use in video tutorials?",
  "response": "Okay, finding free and legal instrumental music for video tutorials can be tricky, but there are some excellent resources out there. Here are some good sources, categorized for clarity:\n\n**1. Royalty-Free Music Libraries (with free tiers/options):**\n\n*   **YouTube Audio Library:** (studio.youtube.com/channel/UC/music) This is built right into YouTube Studio.  It's a HUGE library, searchable by genre, mood, instrument, duration, and attribution requirements (very important!).  The license is straightforward \u2013 you can use it on YouTube videos (and other platforms too, check the terms) and usually only need to give attribution in your video description.  **This is usually the FIRST place you should look.**\n\n*   **Epidemic Sound (30-Day Free Trial):**  Epidemic Sound has a vast library of high-quality music and sound effects. They have a subscription service, but they often offer a free trial period.  If you sign up for a trial, you can download a bunch of tracks and use them in your tutorials as long as you continue to pay for the license after the trial. **IMPORTANT:** Even if you stop subscribing, the tracks you used *while subscribed* are often still licensed for your projects indefinitely (check their terms to confirm).\n\n*   **Artlist (Free Plan/Free Music Section):** Similar to Epidemic Sound, Artlist offers a subscription-based service with a large, curated library. They sometimes offer a completely free plan with a limited selection of music and sound effects.  Always read the license carefully.\n\n*   **Bensound:** (bensound.com) Offers a variety of royalty-free tracks with different licenses. Some tracks are free to use with attribution (usually just a credit in the video description), while others require a paid license. It's easy to find by genre.\n\n*   **AudioJungle:** (audiojungle.net) Owned by Envato, this is a marketplace rather than a subscription service. You buy individual tracks.  While not *entirely* free, they often have free files available each month.  Check their freebies section.  It's a good way to build up a library slowly.\n\n*   **Pond5:** (pond5.com) Another marketplace with individual track purchases. Similar to AudioJungle, they frequently offer free clips (including music) weekly. Check their \"Free Files of the Week\" section.\n\n**2. Creative Commons Music Platforms:**\n\n*   **Free Music Archive (FMA):** (freemusicarchive.org)  A curated collection of Creative Commons licensed music.  The license terms vary widely depending on the specific track.  Some require attribution, some are completely free to use, and some might have restrictions (e.g., non-commercial use only). **Read the license for each track carefully.** It's harder to search compared to paid platforms.\n\n*   **Jamendo:** (jamendo.com) Offers a wide selection of Creative Commons music.  Again, pay close attention to the specific license terms for each track.  They have a free plan with more limited use and a paid plan for commercial projects.\n\n*   **CCmixter:** (ccmixter.org) A community-driven site where artists share their music under Creative Commons licenses.  It's primarily focused on music for remixing and sampling, but you can find some good instrumental tracks. Again, pay CLOSE attention to each individual tracks license.\n\n**3. Individual Artists Offering Free Music:**\n\n*   **Search on SoundCloud:** SoundCloud is a great place to discover independent musicians.  Many artists offer their music for free download or use under Creative Commons licenses.  Use search terms like \"royalty-free instrumental,\" \"Creative Commons music,\" or \"free background music.\" ALWAYS double check license.\n\n*   **Individual Artist Websites/YouTube Channels:** Many composers and musicians have their own websites or YouTube channels where they offer free instrumental music for use in videos.  Search for terms like \"free background music composer\" or \"royalty-free music for YouTube.\"  Look for artists who specifically cater to vloggers, YouTubers, and tutorial creators.\n\n**Important Considerations and Best Practices:**\n\n*   **Read the License Carefully:** This is the MOST important thing.  Before using any music, **thoroughly read and understand the license terms.**  Pay attention to:\n    *   **Attribution requirements:**  Does the artist require you to give them credit in your video description? If so, how?\n    *   **Commercial vs. Non-Commercial Use:**  Is the music free to use only for personal, non-commercial projects, or can you use it for videos that you monetize?\n    *   **Modification Restrictions:**  Are you allowed to edit or modify the music?\n    *   **Revocation:**  Can the license be revoked at any time? (This is less common, but worth checking).\n\n*   **Keep Records of Licenses:** Save copies of the licenses or screenshots of the license terms for each track you use.  This is important for proving that you have the right to use the music if you ever receive a copyright claim.\n\n*   **Attribution:**  If the license requires attribution, be sure to include it prominently in your video description.  Follow the artist's instructions exactly.  A typical attribution might look like this:\n\n    ```\n    Music: \"Title of Track\" by [Artist Name]\n    Source: [Platform where you found the music - e.g., Bensound.com]\n    License: [License Name - e.g., Creative Commons Attribution 3.0]\n    [Link to the license - if provided]\n    ```\n\n*   **Copyright Claims:** Even if you've done everything correctly, you might still receive a copyright claim on YouTube. This doesn't necessarily mean you've done anything wrong. It could be a false positive. You can usually dispute the claim by providing proof of your license.\n\n*   **Quality:**  While free music is great, be mindful of the audio quality.  Make sure the music is well-produced and doesn't sound amateurish or distorted.\n\n*   **Looping and Editing:** Don't be afraid to loop or edit music to fit the length of your tutorial.  Most video editing software makes it easy to trim, loop, and fade music.\n\n*   **Consider Your Brand:** Choose music that aligns with the tone and style of your videos and your overall brand.\n\n*   **Use Filters:** When searching these sites, make use of the filters to find the exact type of music you want (e.g., \"upbeat\", \"corporate\", \"electronic\").\n\nBy using these resources and following these best practices, you can find great instrumental music for your video tutorials without breaking the bank or infringing on anyone's copyright. Good luck!\n",
